      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe overwhelming dominance of **25 °C (298.15 K)** reflects a long-standing convention in solution thermodynamics: this temperature is the standard reference state for tabulating thermodynamic quantities, and most potentiometric/calorimetric experiments are thermostatted to it for direct comparability. The second most common temperature, **20 °C** (~8.7%), likely reflects older European laboratory practice and some biological studies. The **37 °C** cluster (~2.2%) corresponds to physiological temperature measurements relevant to medicinal and bioinorganic chemistry. Notably, every single record in the database has a temperature value — there are no missing temperature entries.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (`ligandmetal_stability_measured`, N = 79,063)*",
